{"title_page": "Emad Shahin", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist|name = Emad Shahin\n|image =Emad Shahin.jpeg\n |native_name_lang = \u0639\u0645\u0627\u062f \u0634\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646|birth_date = {{birth date and age |1957|8|24|mf=y}}|fields = [[Political Science]], [[Middle Eastern Studies]]|alma_mater = [[Johns Hopkins University]]<br>[[American University in Cairo]]|website = http://emadshahin.com|awards = IIIT Distinguished Scholar Award, AUC Excellence in Undergraduate Teaching Award|workplaces = [[Georgetown University]], [[American University in Cairo]], [[Harvard University]], [[Notre Dame University]], [[Boston University]], [[George Washington University]] Al Akhawayn University in Ifrane, Morocco|image_size = }}\n\n'''Emad Shahin''' ( Also '''Emad El-Din Shahin''', {{lang-ar|\u0639\u0645\u0627\u062f \u0634\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646}}; born August 24, 1957) is an Egyptian professor of political science. He is currently a visiting professor at the School of Foreign Service at [[Georgetown University]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Emad Shahin {{!}} School of Foreign Service {{!}} Georgetown University|url = https://sfs.georgetown.edu/Emad-Shahin|website = sfs.georgetown.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-15|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150910165814/https://sfs.georgetown.edu/Emad-Shahin|archive-date = 2015-09-10|url-status = dead}}</ref> He is editor-in-chief of The Oxford Encyclopedia of Islam and Politics,<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Oxford Encyclopedia of Islam and Politics: Emad El-Din Shahin                         - Oxford University Press|url = http://ukcatalogue.oup.com/product/9780199739356.do|website = ukcatalogue.oup.com|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> and professor of public policy at [[The American University in Cairo]] (on leave).<ref>{{Cite web|title = Faculty Profile|url = http://www.aucegypt.edu/fac/emadshahin|website = http://www.aucegypt.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-15|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170726075041/http://www.aucegypt.edu/fac/emadshahin|archive-date = 2017-07-26|url-status = dead}}</ref> His work focuses on Comparative Politics, Democracy and Political Reform in Muslim societies, Islam and Politics, and Political Economy of the Middle East.\n\n== Education ==\nShahin holds a Ph.D. (1989) from the [[Johns Hopkins School of Advanced International Studies]], M.A. (1983) and BA (1980) from the [[American University in Cairo]].\n\n== Career ==\nRecently, Shahin was affiliated with [[The Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Emad El-Din Shahin {{!}} Wilson Center|url = https://www.wilsoncenter.org/person/emad-el-din-shahin|website = www.wilsoncenter.org|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> and Institute for Religion, Culture and Public Life at [[Columbia University]].\n\nPreviously, Shahin was the Henry R. Luce Associate Professor of Religion, Conflict and Peacebuilding, [[University of Notre Dame|University of Notre Dame's Kroc Institute for International Peace Studies]], (2009-2012) and was affiliated with [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|the Kennedy School of Government]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Emad Shahin - Harvard - Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs|url = http://belfercenter.ksg.harvard.edu/experts/957/emad_shahin.html|website = belfercenter.ksg.harvard.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> and the Islamic Legal Studies Program at [[Harvard Law School]] (2006-2009).\n\n== Publications ==\nShahin has authored, co-authored and co-edited six books, and has more than 50 scholarly publications.\n\n'''Books:'''\n\n''Political Ascent: Contemporary Islamic Movements in North Africa'' (Boulder, Colorado: [[Westview Press]], 1998). Paperback edition. {{ISBN|978-0813336176}}\n\n''Political Ascent: Contemporary Islamic Movements in North Africa'' (Boulder, Colorado: Westview Press, 1997). Hardcover edition.\n\n''Through Muslim Eyes: Muhammad Rashid Rida and the West'' (Herndon, VA: International Institute for Islamic Thought, 1993). Hardcover and paperback editions. {{ISBN|978-1565641419}}\n\n'''Edited and Co-authored Work:'''\n\nEditor in Chief, ''The Oxford Encyclopedia of Islam and Politics,'' 2 vols.([[Oxford University Press]], 2014). {{ISBN|978-0199998050}}\n\nCo-editor with John L. Esposito, ''The Oxford Handbook of Islam and Politics'' (Oxford University Press, 2013). {{ISBN|978-0195395891}}\n\nCo-editor with Nathan Brown, ''The Struggle over Democracy in the Middle East and North Africa'' ([[Routledge]], 2010).\n\nCo-Author, ''Islam and Democracy: Toward an Effective Citizenship'' [in Arabic] (Street Law and Center for the Study of Islam and Democracy, 2005).\n\nNorth Africa section editor, ''Modernist Islam: A Source Book'', Kurzman, Charles, ed., (Oxford University Press, 2002).\n\n'''Select Book Chapters and Articles:'''\n\n\"The Egyptian Revolution: The Spirit of Tahrir Square,\" ''Journal of the Middle East and Africa,'' 3:46-69, 2012.\n\n\"Political Parties in Egypt: Alive, but not Kicking,\" in Lawson, Kay and Saad Eddin Ibrahim, eds., ''Political Parties and Democracy: The Arab World'' (Praeger Publishers, 2010).\n\n\"Democratic Transformation in Egypt: Controlled Reforms\u2026Frustrated Hopes,\" in Brown, Nathan and Emad El-Din Shahin, eds. ''The Struggle over Democracy in the Middle East and North Africa'' (Routledge, 2010).\n\n\"Egypt,\" with Nathan Brown, in Angrist, Michele Penner ed., ''Politics and Society in the Contemporary Middle East'' (Lynne Reinner, 2010)''.''\n\n\"Egypt,\" in ''Encyclopedia of Islamic Political Thought,'' eds. Gerhard B\u00f6wering, Patricia Crone, WadadKadi, Devin Stewart, and M. Qasim Zaman ([[Princeton University Press]], 2013)\n\n\"Toleration in Modern Islamic Polity: Contemporary Islamist Views,\" in Creppell, Ingrid, Stephen Macedo, and Russel Hardin, eds., ''Toleration on Trial'' (Lexington Books, 2008).\n\n\"Political Islam in Egypt,\" in Emerson, Michael and Richard Youngs, eds., ''Political Islam and European Foreign Policy'' (Brussels: Center for European Policy Studies, 2007): 65\u201385.\n\n\"Egypt: The Year of the Elections and Elusive Political Reforms,\" in the ''Mediterranean Yearbook Med.2006'' (Barcelona: European Institute of the Mediterranean, 2006): 129\u2013131.\n\n\"Egypt\u2019s Moment of Reform: A Reality or an Illusion?\" in Emerson, Michael, ed., ''Democratization in the European Neighbourhood'' (Brussels: Center for European Policy Studies, 2005): 117\u2013130; also available as ''CEPS Policy Brief'', No. 78 (July 2005): 1\u20136.\n\n\"Political Islam: Ready for Engagement?\" Working paper No. 3 (Madrid: FRIDE, February 2005).\n\nContributed twenty-two entries on: Amarah, Muhammad; Ashmawi, Muhammad Said; Bel Haj, Ali; Berbers; Cairo; al-Fustat; Ghazan Khan, Mahmud; IbnTulun, Ahmad; Islamic Jihad Community; Jabiri, Muhammad Abid; Khayr al-Din al-Tunisi; Majd, Ahmad Kamal Abul al-; Mahmud II; Bin Nabi, Malik; al-Maqrizi, Taqi al-Din; Nizam al-Mulk; Qarawiyin Mosque; al-Rawdah; Sharawi, Shaykh Muhammad Mutawali; Suleyman, Mawlay; Thaalibi, Abd al-Aziz; Yassin, Abd al-Salam.\n\n\"The Foreign Policy of the Islamic Salvation Front in Algeria,\" ''Islam and Christian-Muslim Relations'',  the Center for Christian-Muslim Understanding, Georgetown University, Vol. 14, No. 2 (Spring 2003): 121\u2013143.\n\nSix introductions for the chapters on Muhammad `Abduh, Qassim Amin, Khayr al-Din al-Tunsi, Muhammad Rashid Rida, Abd al-Hamid IbnBadis, and Rifa`a al-Tahtawi, in Kurzman, Charles, ed., ''Modernist Islam: A Source Book'' (Oxford University Press, 2002): 31, 40, 50, 61, 77, and 93.\n\n\"Secularism and Nationalism: The Political Discourse of Abd al-Salam Yassin,\" in ''Islamism and Secularism in North Africa'', John Rudey (ed.). (Saint Martin's, 1994): 167\u201386.\n\n\"Tunisia\u2019s Renaissance Party: The Rise and Repression of an Islamic Movement,\" ''Middle East Insight'',Vol. 11, No. 2(January\u2013February 1995): 29\u201335.\n\n\"Under the Shadow of the Imam: Morocco\u2019s Diverse Islamic Movements,\" ''Middle East Insight'',Vol. 11, No. 2 ''(''January\u2013February 1995): 40\u201345.\n\n\"Algeria: The Limits to Democracy,\" ''Middle East Insight'', Vol. 8, No. 6 (July\u2013October, 1992): 10\u201319.\n\n\"Islam, Democracy and The West: Ending the Cycle of Denial,\" in Mona Abu al-Fadl (ed.), ''Proceedings of the 21st Annual Conference of the Association of Muslim Social Scientists'', (Virginia: IIIT, 1993): 495\u2013501.\n\n\"Muhammad Rashid Rida\u2019s Perspectives on the West as Reflected in ''Al-Manar'',\" ''The Muslim World'', Vol. 79, No. 2 (April, 1989): 113\u201332.\n\n== Media Appearances ==\nDr Shahin's op-eds were published in [[The New York Times]], [[The Washington Post]],<ref>{{Cite news|title = Egypt can stop its spiral toward radicalization|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/egypt-can-stop-its-spiral-toward-radicalization/2014/02/21/6891e9c8-98ee-11e3-80ac-63a8ba7f7942_story.html|newspaper = The Washington Post|date = 2014-02-21|access-date = 2015-10-15|issn = 0190-8286|language = en|first = Emad|last = Shahin}}</ref> [[The Guardian]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Emad El-Din Shahin|url = https://www.theguardian.com/profile/emad-el-din-shahin|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> [[CNN]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Why Egypt needs a second revolution - CNN.com|url = http://www.cnn.com/2011/11/22/opinion/shahin-egypt/index.html|website = CNN|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> [[The Atlantic|Atlantic Monthly]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Emad El-Din Shahin|url = https://www.theatlantic.com/author/emad-shahin/|website = The Atlantic|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> [[Foreign Policy]], [[Al-Ahram]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = \u062f. \u0639\u0645\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0634\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646 - \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0645\u064a|url = http://www.ahram.org.eg/WriterArticles/1821/2013/0.aspx|website = www.ahram.org.eg|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> and [[Al Shorouk (Egyptian newspaper)|Al-Shorouk]]. He has also made appearances with [[Charlie Rose]], Diane Rhem Show, [[Christiane Amanpour]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Egypt suppressing \"any voice of dissent\" - CNN Video|url = http://edition.cnn.com/videos/world/2014/01/28/christiane-amanpour-emad-shahin-egypt-morsy-morsi-sisi.cnn|website = CNN|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> [[National Public Radio (United States)|NPR]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Examining The Years Since Egypt's Arab Spring|url = https://www.npr.org/2015/02/11/385396424/examining-the-4-years-since-egypts-arab-spring|website = NPR.org|accessdate = 2015-10-16|first = Leila|last = Fadel}}</ref> [[CNN]], [[BBC News (TV channel)|BBC]], [[CBC Canada]], [[Voice of America]], [[The Huffington Post|Huffington Post]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Emad Shahin|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/emad-shahin/|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> [[Al Jazeera English|Al-Jazeera]] Arabic and English.\n\n== Political Case ==\nIn January 2014 Shahin was accused in a case known as \"Grand Espionage\" The charges included: espionage, leading an illegal organization, providing a banned organization with information and financial support, calling for the suspension of the constitution, preventing state institutions and authorities from performing their functions, harming national unity and social harmony, and causing to change the government by force. Shahin issued a statement in which he refuted all allegations.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Statement to My Students, Family, and Friends - Dr. Emad Shahin|url = http://emadshahin.com/?page_id=1043|website = Dr. Emad Shahin|accessdate = 2015-10-15|language = en}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the charges, Shahin received international support from fellow scholars,<ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3MXMWSvJdjA|accessdate = 2015-10-16|last = Lynch|first = Marc|title = Marc Lynch on Emad Shahin}}<nowiki>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3MXMWSvJdjA</nowiki></ref> academic institutions<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://esfdelhi.blogspot.in/2014/01/indian-academicians-in-solidarity-with.html|title = Indian Academicians in Solidarity with Egyptian Political Scientist Prof. Emad Shahin|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> and organizations among those were The Middle East Studies Association of North America (MESA),<ref>{{Cite web|title = Letters on Egypt|url = http://mesa.arizona.edu/committees/academic-freedom/intervention/letters-egypt.html#egypt20140204|website = mesa.arizona.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences Letter - Dr. Emad Shahin|url = http://emadshahin.com/?p=680|website = Dr. Emad Shahin|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en}}</ref>[[Center for Contemporary Arab Studies]], [[Georgetown University]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Center for Contemporary Arab Studies, Georgetown University Letter - Dr. Emad Shahin|url = http://emadshahin.com/?p=662#sthash.38zsQsoB.dpuf|website = Dr. Emad Shahin|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en}}</ref> The International Steering Committee of the Community of Democracies,<ref>{{Cite web|title = The International Steering Committee of the Community of Democracies Statement - Dr. Emad Shahin|url = http://emadshahin.com/?p=676|website = Dr. Emad Shahin|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, 2015 Shahin was sentenced to death in absentia by a Cairo court, along with former Egyptian President [[Mohamed Morsy]] and 100 others.<ref>http://edition.cnn.com/2015/05/16/africa/egypt-mohamed-morsy-verdict</ref> On June 16, 2015 the death sentence was confirmed. He issued another statement.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Statement by Prof. Emad Shahin on his death sentence - Dr. Emad Shahin|url = http://emadshahin.com/?p=1839|website = Dr. Emad Shahin|accessdate = 2015-10-15|language = en}}</ref>\n\nMore than 40 scholars, colleagues and friends of Emad Shahin, including [[Joel Beinin]], Eva Bellin, [[Nathan J. Brown (political scientist)|Nathan J. Brown]], [[Rochelle Davis (scholar)|Rochelle Davis]], [[Larry Diamond]], Michele Dunne, John P. Entelis, [[John Esposito|John L Esposito]], [[Khaled Fahmy]], Ellis Goldberg, [[Daniel C. Kurtzer|Ambassador Daniel Kurtzer]], [[Roger Owen (historian)|Roger Owen]], James Piscatori, [[William B. Quandt]], [[Tariq Ramadan]], Robert Springborg, Ambassador (retired) William A. Rugh, [[Alfred Stepan]] and [[I. William Zartman]] wrote an open letter in which they expressed deep concern over the provisional sentence of death. They called on governments throughout the world \"to speak out and communicate their concern to their Egyptian counterparts and to rebuff any efforts to restrict Professor Shahin\u2019s movements, speech, and activities.\" The scholars confirmed that \"based on our personal knowledge of Professor Shahin\u2019s character, activities, and scholarship, we state that the charges are so utterly alien to his character as to lack any credibility whatsoever.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Letter of Support by Colleagues and Personal Friends of Emad Shahin {{!}} Middle East Research and Information Project|url = http://www.merip.org/letter-support-colleagues-personal-friends-emad-shahin|website = www.merip.org|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref>\n\nMESA also issued another letter in protest of provisional sentencing to death of Dr. Emad Shahin.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Letters on Egypt|url = http://mesana.org/committees/academic-freedom/intervention/letters-egypt.html#Egypt20150601|website = mesana.org|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> The statement called on the Egyptian government \"to rescind Dr. Shahin\u2019s conviction immediately and dismiss all charges against him\". Similarly, the Committee of Concerned Scientists joined the numerous academics who condemned this sentence which it described as \" retaliation for Shahin\u2019s pro-democracy stance.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Death Sentence in Absentia of  Egyptian Scholar Called Baseless|url = http://concernedscientists.org/2015/06/death-sentence-in-absentia-of-egyptian-scholar-called-baseless/|website = Committee of Concerned Scientists|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en}}</ref>\n\nShahin's case acquired a lot of media coverage in the US: [[The New York Times]],<ref>{{Cite news|title = Renowned Scholar in Egypt Charged With Espionage|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/23/world/middleeast/egypt.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2014-01-22|access-date = 2015-10-16|issn = 0362-4331|first = David D.|last = Kirkpatrick}}</ref> [[CNN]].<ref name=\":0\" /> His story was also featured in international media outlets such as VG,<ref>{{Cite web|title = I april snakket professoren p\u00e5 Universitetet i Oslo. N\u00e5 er han d\u00f8mt til d\u00f8den i Egypt|url = http://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/egypt/i-april-snakket-professoren-paa-universitetet-i-oslo-naa-er-han-doemt-til-doeden-i-egypt/a/23453838/|website = VG|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[Die Welt]],<ref>{{Cite news|title = Klassische Merkmale faschistischer Herrschaft|url = https://www.welt.de/politik/ausland/article141857297/Klassische-Merkmale-faschistischer-Herrschaft.html|newspaper = Welt Online|date = 2015-06-03|access-date = 2015-10-16|first = Eva Marie|last = Kogel}}</ref> [[BILD]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = BILD-Interview - Ein zum TodeVerurteilter klagt an!|url = http://www.bild.de/politik/ausland/politiker/exil-politiker-packt-aus-41270160.bild.html|website = BILD.de|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Un profesor de Georgetown, compa\u00f1ero de Mursi en el cadalso|url = http://www.elmundo.es/internacional/2015/06/17/55806bc8ca47411a4d8b45bc.html|website = ELMUNDO|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> La Presse Canada,<ref>{{Cite web|title = PressReader.com - Connecting People Through News|url = http://www.pressreader.com/canada/la-presse/20150520/281706908266973/TextView|website = www.pressreader.com|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[Internazionale]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Record di condanne a morte in Egitto - Catherine Cornet|url = http://www.internazionale.it/opinione/catherine-cornet/2015/05/21/record-di-condanne-a-morte-in-egitto|website = Internazionale|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = it}}</ref> [[Le Figaro]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.lefigaro.fr/international/2015/06/16/01003-20150616ARTFIG00284-la-peine-de-mort-de-mohammed-morsi-confirmee.php|title = La peine de mort de Mohammed Morsi confirm\u00e9e|date = June 16, 2015|accessdate = October 16, 2015|website = Le Figaro|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the sentence, Shahin made interviews with international media including: Vice news,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Egypt Court Issues Death Penalty for Georgetown Political Science Professor {{!}} VICE News|url = https://news.vice.com/article/egypt-court-issues-death-penalty-for-georgetown-political-science-professor|website = VICE News|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en-US}}</ref> [[Agence France-Presse|AFP]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Convicted Egypt academic denounces 'reign of terror'|url = https://news.yahoo.com/convicted-egypt-academic-denounces-reign-terror-142930477.html|website = Yahoo News|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[HuffPost Live|Huffpost Live]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = HuffPost Live|url = http://live.huffingtonpost.com/r/archive/segment/sentenced-to-death-in-egypt-one-mans-hope-for-democracy/555e238b78c90ac8640000bf|website = live.huffingtonpost.com|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[National Public Radio (United States)|National Public Radio,]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Visting {{sic|nolink=y}} Georgetown Professor Among Those Egypt Sentences To Death|url = https://www.npr.org/2015/05/22/408680086/visting-georgetown-professor-among-those-egypt-sentences-to-death|website = NPR.org|accessdate = 2015-10-16|first = Morning|last = Edition}}</ref> [[Colorado Public Radio]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Visiting DU scholar Emad Shahin sentenced to death in Egypt|url = http://www.cpr.org/news/story/visiting-du-scholar-emad-shahin-sentenced-death-egypt#sthash.d3EAOloP.dpuf|website = Colorado Public Radio|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> Boston NPR's National Radio,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Egypt's Transformation, Before And After Morsi's Fall|url = http://onpoint.wbur.org/2015/05/28/egypt-revolution-tahrir-morsi-al-sisi-changes|website = onpoint|date = 2015-05-28|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[Al Jazeera English|Aljazeera English]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Q&A: Egypt death sentences 'a bargaining chip'|url = http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/05/qa-egypt-death-sentences-bargaining-chip-150518072011962.html|website = www.aljazeera.com|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> and Georgetown's Vox Populi.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Vox Populi|url = http://blog.georgetownvoice.com/2015/06/05/egypts-sisi-regime-sentences-sfs-professor-to-death-final-verdict-pending/|website = blog.georgetownvoice.com|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shahin, Emad}}\n[[Category:Egyptian scholars]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Egyptian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist|name = Emad Shahin\n|image =Emad Shahin.jpeg\n |native_name_lang = \u0639\u0645\u0627\u062f \u0634\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646|birth_date = {{birth date and age |1957|8|24|mf=y}}|fields = [[Political Science]], [[Middle Eastern Studies]]|alma_mater = [[Johns Hopkins University]]<br>[[American University in Cairo]]|website = http://emadshahin.com|awards = IIIT Distinguished Scholar Award, AUC Excellence in Undergraduate Teaching Award|workplaces = [[Georgetown University]], [[American University in Cairo]], [[Harvard University]], [[Notre Dame University]], [[Boston University]], [[George Washington University]] Al Akhawayn University in Ifrane, Morocco|image_size = }}\n\n'''Emad Shahin''' ( Also '''Emad El-Din Shahin''', {{lang-ar|\u0639\u0645\u0627\u062f \u0634\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646}}; born August 24, 1957) is an Egyptian professor of political science. He is currently a visiting professor at the School of Foreign Service at [[Georgetown University]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Emad Shahin {{!}} School of Foreign Service {{!}} Georgetown University|url = https://sfs.georgetown.edu/Emad-Shahin|website = sfs.georgetown.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-15|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150910165814/https://sfs.georgetown.edu/Emad-Shahin|archive-date = 2015-09-10|url-status = dead}}</ref> He is editor-in-chief of The Oxford Encyclopedia of Islam and Politics,<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Oxford Encyclopedia of Islam and Politics: Emad El-Din Shahin                         - Oxford University Press|url = http://ukcatalogue.oup.com/product/9780199739356.do|website = ukcatalogue.oup.com|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> and professor of public policy at [[The American University in Cairo]] (on leave).<ref>{{Cite web|title = Faculty Profile|url = http://www.aucegypt.edu/fac/emadshahin|website = http://www.aucegypt.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-15|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170726075041/http://www.aucegypt.edu/fac/emadshahin|archive-date = 2017-07-26|url-status = dead}}</ref> His work focuses on Comparative Politics, Democracy and Political Reform in Muslim societies, Islam and Politics, and Political Economy of the Middle East.\n\n== Education ==\nShahin holds a Ph.D. (1989) from the [[Johns Hopkins School of Advanced International Studies]], M.A. (1983) and BA (1980) from the [[American University in Cairo]].\n\n== Career ==\nRecently, Shahin was affiliated with [[The Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Emad El-Din Shahin {{!}} Wilson Center|url = https://www.wilsoncenter.org/person/emad-el-din-shahin|website = www.wilsoncenter.org|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> and Institute for Religion, Culture and Public Life at [[Columbia University]].\n\nPreviously, Shahin was the Henry R. Luce Associate Professor of Religion, Conflict and Peacebuilding, [[University of Notre Dame|University of Notre Dame's Kroc Institute for International Peace Studies]], (2009-2012) and was affiliated with [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|the Kennedy School of Government]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Emad Shahin - Harvard - Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs|url = http://belfercenter.ksg.harvard.edu/experts/957/emad_shahin.html|website = belfercenter.ksg.harvard.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> and the Islamic Legal Studies Program at [[Harvard Law School]] (2006-2009).\n\n== Publications ==\nShahin has authored, co-authored and co-edited six books, and has more than 50 scholarly publications.\n\n'''Books:'''\n\n''Political Ascent: Contemporary Islamic Movements in North Africa'' (Boulder, Colorado: [[Westview Press]], 1998). Paperback edition. {{ISBN|978-0813336176}}\n\n''Political Ascent: Contemporary Islamic Movements in North Africa'' (Boulder, Colorado: Westview Press, 1997). Hardcover edition.\n\n''Through Muslim Eyes: Muhammad Rashid Rida and the West'' (Herndon, VA: International Institute for Islamic Thought, 1993). Hardcover and paperback editions. {{ISBN|978-1565641419}}\n\n'''Edited and Co-authored Work:'''\n\nEditor in Chief, ''The Oxford Encyclopedia of Islam and Politics,'' 2 vols.([[Oxford University Press]], 2014). {{ISBN|978-0199998050}}\n\nCo-editor with John L. Esposito, ''The Oxford Handbook of Islam and Politics'' (Oxford University Press, 2013). {{ISBN|978-0195395891}}\n\nCo-editor with Nathan Brown, ''The Struggle over Democracy in the Middle East and North Africa'' ([[Routledge]], 2010).\n\nCo-Author, ''Islam and Democracy: Toward an Effective Citizenship'' [in Arabic] (Street Law and Center for the Study of Islam and Democracy, 2005).\n\nNorth Africa section editor, ''Modernist Islam: A Source Book'', Kurzman, Charles, ed., (Oxford University Press, 2002).\n\n'''Select Book Chapters and Articles:'''\n\n\"The Egyptian Revolution: The Spirit of Tahrir Square,\" ''Journal of the Middle East and Africa,'' 3:46-69, 2012.\n\n\"Political Parties in Egypt: Alive, but not Kicking,\" in Lawson, Kay and Saad Eddin Ibrahim, eds., ''Political Parties and Democracy: The Arab World'' (Praeger Publishers, 2010).\n\n\"Democratic Transformation in Egypt: Controlled Reforms\u2026Frustrated Hopes,\" in Brown, Nathan and Emad El-Din Shahin, eds. ''The Struggle over Democracy in the Middle East and North Africa'' (Routledge, 2010).\n\n\"Egypt,\" with Nathan Brown, in Angrist, Michele Penner ed., ''Politics and Society in the Contemporary Middle East'' (Lynne Reinner, 2010)''.''\n\n\"Egypt,\" in ''Encyclopedia of Islamic Political Thought,'' eds. Gerhard B\u00f6wering, Patricia Crone, WadadKadi, Devin Stewart, and M. Qasim Zaman ([[Princeton University Press]], 2013)\n\n\"Toleration in Modern Islamic Polity: Contemporary Islamist Views,\" in Creppell, Ingrid, Stephen Macedo, and Russel Hardin, eds., ''Toleration on Trial'' (Lexington Books, 2008).\n\n\"Political Islam in Egypt,\" in Emerson, Michael and Richard Youngs, eds., ''Political Islam and European Foreign Policy'' (Brussels: Center for European Policy Studies, 2007): 65-85.\n\n\"Egypt: The Year of the Elections and Elusive Political Reforms,\" in the ''Mediterranean Yearbook Med.2006'' (Barcelona: European Institute of the Mediterranean, 2006): 129-131.\n\n\"Egypt\u2019s Moment of Reform: A Reality or an Illusion?\" in Emerson, Michael, ed., ''Democratization in the European Neighbourhood'' (Brussels: Center for European Policy Studies, 2005): 117-130; also available as ''CEPS Policy Brief'', No. 78 (July 2005): 1-6.\n\n\"Political Islam: Ready for Engagement?\" Working paper No. 3 (Madrid: FRIDE, February 2005).\n\nContributed twenty-two entries on: Amarah, Muhammad; Ashmawi, Muhammad Said; Bel Haj, Ali; Berbers; Cairo; al-Fustat; Ghazan Khan, Mahmud; IbnTulun, Ahmad; Islamic Jihad Community; Jabiri, Muhammad Abid; Khayr al-Din al-Tunisi; Majd, Ahmad Kamal Abul al-; Mahmud II; Bin Nabi, Malik; al-Maqrizi, Taqi al-Din; Nizam al-Mulk; Qarawiyin Mosque; al-Rawdah; Sharawi, Shaykh Muhammad Mutawali; Suleyman, Mawlay; Thaalibi, Abd al-Aziz; Yassin, Abd al-Salam.\n\n\"The Foreign Policy of the Islamic Salvation Front in Algeria,\" ''Islam and Christian-Muslim Relations'',  the Center for Christian-Muslim Understanding, Georgetown University, Vol. 14, No. 2 (Spring 2003): 121-143.\n\nSix introductions for the chapters on Muhammad `Abduh, Qassim Amin, Khayr al-Din al-Tunsi, Muhammad Rashid Rida, Abd al-Hamid IbnBadis, and Rifa`a al-Tahtawi, in Kurzman, Charles, ed., ''Modernist Islam: A Source Book'' (Oxford University Press, 2002): 31, 40, 50, 61, 77, and 93.\n\n\"Secularism and Nationalism: The Political Discourse of Abd al-Salam Yassin,\" in ''Islamism and Secularism in North Africa'', John Rudey (ed.). (Saint Martin\u2019s, 1994): 167-86.\n\n\"Tunisia\u2019s Renaissance Party: The Rise and Repression of an Islamic Movement,\" ''Middle East Insight'',Vol. 11, No. 2(January\u2013February 1995): 29-35.\n\n\"Under the Shadow of the Imam: Morocco\u2019s Diverse Islamic Movements,\" ''Middle East Insight'',Vol. 11, No. 2 ''(''January\u2013February 1995): 40-45.\n\n\"Algeria: The Limits to Democracy,\" ''Middle East Insight'', Vol. 8, No. 6 (July\u2013October, 1992): 10-19.\n\n\"Islam, Democracy and The West: Ending the Cycle of Denial,\" in Mona Abu al-Fadl (ed.), ''Proceedings of the 21st Annual Conference of the Association of Muslim Social Scientists'', (Virginia: IIIT, 1993): 495-501.\n\n\"Muhammad Rashid Rida\u2019s Perspectives on the West as Reflected in ''Al-Manar'',\" ''The Muslim World'', Vol. 79, No. 2 (April, 1989): 113-32.\n\n== Media Appearances ==\nDr Shahin\u2019s op-eds were published in [[The New York Times]], [[The Washington Post]],<ref>{{Cite news|title = Egypt can stop its spiral toward radicalization|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/egypt-can-stop-its-spiral-toward-radicalization/2014/02/21/6891e9c8-98ee-11e3-80ac-63a8ba7f7942_story.html|newspaper = The Washington Post|date = 2014-02-21|access-date = 2015-10-15|issn = 0190-8286|language = en|first = Emad|last = Shahin}}</ref> [[The Guardian]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Emad El-Din Shahin|url = https://www.theguardian.com/profile/emad-el-din-shahin|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> [[CNN]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Why Egypt needs a second revolution - CNN.com|url = http://www.cnn.com/2011/11/22/opinion/shahin-egypt/index.html|website = CNN|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> [[The Atlantic|Atlantic Monthly]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Emad El-Din Shahin|url = https://www.theatlantic.com/author/emad-shahin/|website = The Atlantic|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> [[Foreign Policy]], [[Al-Ahram]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = \u062f. \u0639\u0645\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0634\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646 - \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0645\u064a|url = http://www.ahram.org.eg/WriterArticles/1821/2013/0.aspx|website = www.ahram.org.eg|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> and [[Al Shorouk (Egyptian newspaper)|Al-Shorouk]]. He has also made appearances with [[Charlie Rose]], Diane Rhem Show, [[Christiane Amanpour]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Egypt suppressing \"any voice of dissent\" - CNN Video|url = http://edition.cnn.com/videos/world/2014/01/28/christiane-amanpour-emad-shahin-egypt-morsy-morsi-sisi.cnn|website = CNN|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> [[National Public Radio (United States)|NPR]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Examining The Years Since Egypt's Arab Spring|url = https://www.npr.org/2015/02/11/385396424/examining-the-4-years-since-egypts-arab-spring|website = NPR.org|accessdate = 2015-10-16|first = Leila|last = Fadel}}</ref> [[CNN]], [[BBC News (TV channel)|BBC]], [[CBC Canada]], [[Voice of America]], [[The Huffington Post|Huffington Post]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Emad Shahin|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/emad-shahin/|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref> [[Al Jazeera English|Al-Jazeera]] Arabic and English.\n\n== Political Case ==\nIn January 2014 Shahin was accused in a case known as \"Grand Espionage\" The charges included: espionage, leading an illegal organization, providing a banned organization with information and financial support, calling for the suspension of the constitution, preventing state institutions and authorities from performing their functions, harming national unity and social harmony, and causing to change the government by force. Shahin issued a statement in which he refuted all allegations.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Statement to My Students, Family, and Friends - Dr. Emad Shahin|url = http://emadshahin.com/?page_id=1043|website = Dr. Emad Shahin|accessdate = 2015-10-15|language = en}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the charges, Shahin received international support from fellow scholars,<ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3MXMWSvJdjA|accessdate = 2015-10-16|last = Lynch|first = Marc|title = Marc Lynch on Emad Shahin}}<nowiki>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3MXMWSvJdjA</nowiki></ref> academic institutions<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://esfdelhi.blogspot.in/2014/01/indian-academicians-in-solidarity-with.html|title = Indian Academicians in Solidarity with Egyptian Political Scientist Prof. Emad Shahin|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> and organizations among those were The Middle East Studies Association of North America (MESA),<ref>{{Cite web|title = Letters on Egypt|url = http://mesa.arizona.edu/committees/academic-freedom/intervention/letters-egypt.html#egypt20140204|website = mesa.arizona.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences Letter - Dr. Emad Shahin|url = http://emadshahin.com/?p=680|website = Dr. Emad Shahin|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en}}</ref>[[Center for Contemporary Arab Studies]], [[Georgetown University]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Center for Contemporary Arab Studies, Georgetown University Letter - Dr. Emad Shahin|url = http://emadshahin.com/?p=662#sthash.38zsQsoB.dpuf|website = Dr. Emad Shahin|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en}}</ref> The International Steering Committee of the Community of Democracies,<ref>{{Cite web|title = The International Steering Committee of the Community of Democracies Statement - Dr. Emad Shahin|url = http://emadshahin.com/?p=676|website = Dr. Emad Shahin|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, 2015 Shahin was sentenced to death in absentia by a Cairo court, along with former Egyptian President [[Mohamed Morsy]] and 100 others.<ref>http://edition.cnn.com/2015/05/16/africa/egypt-mohamed-morsy-verdict</ref> On June 16, 2015 the death sentence was confirmed. He issued another statement.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Statement by Prof. Emad Shahin on his death sentence - Dr. Emad Shahin|url = http://emadshahin.com/?p=1839|website = Dr. Emad Shahin|accessdate = 2015-10-15|language = en}}</ref>\n\nMore than 40 scholars, colleagues and friends of Emad Shahin, including [[Joel Beinin]], Eva Bellin, [[Nathan J. Brown (political scientist)|Nathan J. Brown]], [[Rochelle Davis (scholar)|Rochelle Davis]], [[Larry Diamond]], Michele Dunne, John P. Entelis, [[John Esposito|John L Esposito]], [[Khaled Fahmy]], Ellis Goldberg, [[Daniel C. Kurtzer|Ambassador Daniel Kurtzer]], [[Roger Owen (historian)|Roger Owen]], James Piscatori, [[William B. Quandt]], [[Tariq Ramadan]], Robert Springborg, Ambassador (retired) William A. Rugh, [[Alfred Stepan]] and [[I. William Zartman]] wrote an open letter in which they expressed deep concern over the provisional sentence of death. They called on governments throughout the world \"to speak out and communicate their concern to their Egyptian counterparts and to rebuff any efforts to restrict Professor Shahin\u2019s movements, speech, and activities.\" The scholars confirmed that \"based on our personal knowledge of Professor Shahin\u2019s character, activities, and scholarship, we state that the charges are so utterly alien to his character as to lack any credibility whatsoever.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Letter of Support by Colleagues and Personal Friends of Emad Shahin {{!}} Middle East Research and Information Project|url = http://www.merip.org/letter-support-colleagues-personal-friends-emad-shahin|website = www.merip.org|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref>\n\nMESA also issued another letter in protest of provisional sentencing to death of Dr. Emad Shahin.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Letters on Egypt|url = http://mesana.org/committees/academic-freedom/intervention/letters-egypt.html#Egypt20150601|website = mesana.org|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> The statement called on the Egyptian government \"to rescind Dr. Shahin\u2019s conviction immediately and dismiss all charges against him\". Similarly, the Committee of Concerned Scientists joined the numerous academics who condemned this sentence which it described as \" retaliation for Shahin\u2019s pro-democracy stance.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Death Sentence in Absentia of  Egyptian Scholar Called Baseless|url = http://concernedscientists.org/2015/06/death-sentence-in-absentia-of-egyptian-scholar-called-baseless/|website = Committee of Concerned Scientists|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en}}</ref>\n\nShahin's case acquired a lot of media coverage in the US: [[The New York Times]],<ref>{{Cite news|title = Renowned Scholar in Egypt Charged With Espionage|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/23/world/middleeast/egypt.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2014-01-22|access-date = 2015-10-16|issn = 0362-4331|first = David D.|last = Kirkpatrick}}</ref> [[CNN]].<ref name=\":0\" /> His story was also featured in international media outlets such as VG,<ref>{{Cite web|title = I april snakket professoren p\u00e5 Universitetet i Oslo. N\u00e5 er han d\u00f8mt til d\u00f8den i Egypt|url = http://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/egypt/i-april-snakket-professoren-paa-universitetet-i-oslo-naa-er-han-doemt-til-doeden-i-egypt/a/23453838/|website = VG|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[Die Welt]],<ref>{{Cite news|title = Klassische Merkmale faschistischer Herrschaft|url = https://www.welt.de/politik/ausland/article141857297/Klassische-Merkmale-faschistischer-Herrschaft.html|newspaper = Welt Online|date = 2015-06-03|access-date = 2015-10-16|first = Eva Marie|last = Kogel}}</ref> [[BILD]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = BILD-Interview - Ein zum TodeVerurteilter klagt an!|url = http://www.bild.de/politik/ausland/politiker/exil-politiker-packt-aus-41270160.bild.html|website = BILD.de|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Un profesor de Georgetown, compa\u00f1ero de Mursi en el cadalso|url = http://www.elmundo.es/internacional/2015/06/17/55806bc8ca47411a4d8b45bc.html|website = ELMUNDO|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> La Presse Canada,<ref>{{Cite web|title = PressReader.com - Connecting People Through News|url = http://www.pressreader.com/canada/la-presse/20150520/281706908266973/TextView|website = www.pressreader.com|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[Internazionale]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Record di condanne a morte in Egitto - Catherine Cornet|url = http://www.internazionale.it/opinione/catherine-cornet/2015/05/21/record-di-condanne-a-morte-in-egitto|website = Internazionale|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = it}}</ref> [[Le Figaro]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.lefigaro.fr/international/2015/06/16/01003-20150616ARTFIG00284-la-peine-de-mort-de-mohammed-morsi-confirmee.php|title = La peine de mort de Mohammed Morsi confirm\u00e9e|date = June 16, 2015|accessdate = October 16, 2015|website = Le Figaro|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the sentence, Shahin made interviews with international media including: Vice news,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Egypt Court Issues Death Penalty for Georgetown Political Science Professor {{!}} VICE News|url = https://news.vice.com/article/egypt-court-issues-death-penalty-for-georgetown-political-science-professor|website = VICE News|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en-US}}</ref> [[Agence France-Presse|AFP]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Convicted Egypt academic denounces 'reign of terror'|url = https://news.yahoo.com/convicted-egypt-academic-denounces-reign-terror-142930477.html|website = Yahoo News|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[HuffPost Live|Huffpost Live]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = HuffPost Live|url = http://live.huffingtonpost.com/r/archive/segment/sentenced-to-death-in-egypt-one-mans-hope-for-democracy/555e238b78c90ac8640000bf|website = live.huffingtonpost.com|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[National Public Radio (United States)|National Public Radio,]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Visting {{sic|nolink=y}} Georgetown Professor Among Those Egypt Sentences To Death|url = https://www.npr.org/2015/05/22/408680086/visting-georgetown-professor-among-those-egypt-sentences-to-death|website = NPR.org|accessdate = 2015-10-16|first = Morning|last = Edition}}</ref> [[Colorado Public Radio]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Visiting DU scholar Emad Shahin sentenced to death in Egypt|url = http://www.cpr.org/news/story/visiting-du-scholar-emad-shahin-sentenced-death-egypt#sthash.d3EAOloP.dpuf|website = Colorado Public Radio|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> Boston NPR\u2019s National Radio,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Egypt's Transformation, Before And After Morsi's Fall|url = http://onpoint.wbur.org/2015/05/28/egypt-revolution-tahrir-morsi-al-sisi-changes|website = onpoint|date = 2015-05-28|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> [[Al Jazeera English|Aljazeera English]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Q&A: Egypt death sentences 'a bargaining chip'|url = http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/05/qa-egypt-death-sentences-bargaining-chip-150518072011962.html|website = www.aljazeera.com|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref> and Georgetown's Vox Populi.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Vox Populi|u